Mauritius and other countries first discovered cases of the Omicron strain infection - Xinhua News Agency, Beijing, December 12th. According to Xinhua's foreign correspondent, Mauritius, Cyprus and Malawi recently reported the first cases of the new crown variant virus Omicron strain infection. Mauritius first reported two cases of Omicron strain infection on the 10th. According to the Minister of Health, Kailash Jugtipal, one infected person is a tourist who arrived in Mauritius from South Africa on November 27th, and the other is a local resident who tested positive for nucleic acid on November 30th after contact with a person who recently traveled to South Africa and returned. After hospital isolation treatment, the nucleic acid test results of the two infected people turned negative and they have now returned to their respective residences. The Cyprus Ministry of Health announced on the 10th the first confirmed three cases of Omicron strain infection in the country. These three individuals are students who returned from overseas travel earlier this month and were not hospitalized for treatment as they are all mild cases. To prevent the spread of the Omicron strain, the government of Cyprus is constantly increasing its preventive measures. From December 6th to January 10th, passengers over the age of 12 who enter by air must undergo nucleic acid testing at the airport at their own expense. The Cyprus Ministry of Health also announced on the 10th that it will begin vaccinating children aged 5 to 11 with the Pfizer coronavirus vaccine. Malawi's Health Minister, Kumbuzai Chihenga, said on the 9th that the country has reported its first three cases of the Omnicoke variant of the COVID-19 virus. The country's health department conducted genome sequencing on 12 positive COVID-19 samples collected from November 9th to December 2nd and identified these three cases of infection.
